{"author":{"id":"4bb6c1767e50694cfde61856db22bf137d1651e8a0b5ca858c486db3dd02f280"},"ops":[{"type":3,"timestamp":1774408981,"nonce":"9ziTBaOK83yQ0XoxMsMcgSc5Guk=","message":"**Session update: baseline gap-filling runs and infrastructure notes**\n\n**Gap-filling runs launched:**\n- pert_std=0 rerun (previous run failed to converge, ep_err=0.47)\n- std+update pert_std=0 at ratio 0.3 and ratio 0.5\n- APT+update pert_std=0 at ratio 0.3\n\nThese fill in the pert_std=0 row of the condition matrix so the baseline comparison is valid.\n\n**Signal-dependent noise already implemented:** feedbax already has Multiplicative(Normal(std=motor_noise_std)) + Normal(std=1.8*motor_noise_std), based on Beer, Haggard \u0026 Wolpert (2004). Current motor_noise_std=0.01 (from training hyperparameters). The question is whether this level creates meaningful speed-accuracy tradeoff pressure that would incentivize SISU-conditional velocity modulation. May need a scaling investigation. See Bug: [signal-dependent noise issue to be filed].\n\n**Existing analysis infrastructure:** feedbax has Jacobians, Hessians, PCA, Profiles, Violins, and Tangling in its analysis module, used by part2.plant_perts. These are sufficient for the mechanistic analysis plan — no need to reimplement.\n\n**Adversary network approaches (analysis in progress via Opus agent):**\n- Parameterized adversary: most stable, easiest to train\n- Open-loop neural adversary: fixed perturbation trajectory, no feedback\n- Closed-loop neural adversary: most powerful, adapts to controller state in real time\n- Timing-game variant: adversary watches trial and decides WHEN to emit a perturbation gust (timing as the adversarial degree of freedom rather than direction/magnitude)","files":null}]}